    <para id="para-00008">Paying $1000 a month is not sufficient to pay down the initial $18,000 when the interest rate is 21%. In fact, your unpaid balance will continue to rise. What can you do to pay off the credit card debt?</para>
    </problem>
    <solution id="sol-00001">
    <para id="para-00009">After talking to your credit union, they offer you a loan at 7% interest with monthly installments of $1000 per month over the next 20 months. This is the best possible solution.</para>
    </solution>
    </exercise>
    </example>
    <para id="para-00010">One of the best ways to stay out of debt is to pay off credit card balances in full every month. This is one of the highest interest rate categories you will ever come across. Credit card companies charge up to 21% on unpaid balances, and this is interest paid on items that are losing value daily. If you can manage it, pay off credit cards first.</para>
    <para id="para-00011">Here are a few things the experts suggest keeping in mind: Prepare for the unexpected. What if your employer should lay you off? Have an emergency fund set aside. The rule of thumb is to have at least 6 months of living expenses in a savings account, as losing your job may come without warning. Some experts suggest paying everything with credit cards so that you can account for everything you spend. Others suggest a pay-with-cash approach. Decide which method works better for you. The number one suggestion from experts is to beware of impulse buying. Here is an online app to help you prepare a budget: <link url="https://openstax.org/r/budget_bundle">Budget Maker</link></para>
    </section>
